The department has declared the following species of wildlife to be inherently dangerous to human health and safety and shall establish procedures for denying or issuing a transportation permit for said wildlife:
African buffalo (Syncerus caffer);
Hippopotamus (Hippopotamus amphibius);
Hyenas (family Hyaenidae), all species except aardwolves (Proteles cristatus);
Old world badger (Meles meles);
Lions, jaguars, leopards, or tigers (genus Panthera);
Clouded leopard (Neofelis nebulosa);
Cheetah (Acinonyx jubatus);
Elephants (family Elephantidae);
Rhinoceroses (family Rhinocerotidae);
Gorillas (family Pongidae);
Baboons, drills, or mandrills (genus Papio);
Gelada baboon (Theropithecus gelada);
Gavials (family Gavialidae);
Crocodiles (family Crocodylidae);
Alligators or caimans (family Alligatoridae);
Sea snakes (family Hydrophidae);
Cobras or coral snakes (family Elapidae);
Adders or vipers (family Viperae);
Venomous rear-fanged species (family Colubridae);
Gila monsters or beaded lizards (family Helodermatidae);
Komodo dragon (Varanus komodoensis);
Wolverine (Gulo gulo);
Bears (family Ursidae);
Wolf or wolf hybrids of over twenty-five percent (25%) wolf; or
Cougar or mountain lion (Felis concolor).
